al-but-separate men's and women's rooms, and twenty-first-century uproar over laws like North Carolina's "bathroom bill," Davis reveals how public restrooms are far from marginal or unimportant social spaces. Instead, they are-and always have been-consequential sites in which ideology, institutions, and inequality collide.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aPublic toiletsxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aRestroomsxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aSex rolezUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh  abathroom bill.  abathrooms.  acivil rights.  acomfort stations.  adiscrimination.  agender and sexuality.  agender difference.  agender norms.  agender studies.  agender.  agendered restrooms.  ahistory.  ahuman rights.  ahygiene.  ainclusion.  algbt studies.  amens restroom.  amodern gender.  anonfiction.  anorth carolina.  apolitics.  aprivacy.  apublic health.  apublic restrooms.  arace.  arestrooms.  asocial issues.  asocial science.  asocial spaces.  asocial status.  atrans rights.  atransgender.  awomens restroom.  awomens studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishz978311070474708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020z9783110704532oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press Frontlist eBook-Package 2020z978311069041540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520971660zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520971660423Coveruhttps://ww